sols:
The average value of a function $f(x)$ over an interval $[a,b]$ is given
by

\begin{align*}\frac{1}{b-a}\int_a^b f(x)\, dx\end{align*}

In this case, this is given by

\begin{align*}\frac{1}{2}\int_0^2 xe^x\, dx\end{align*}

Let us then compute the indefinite integral

\begin{align*}\int xe^x\, dx\end{align*}

which we can compute via integration by parts. If we let $u = x$ and
$dv = e^xdx$, then we find that

\begin{align*}\begin{matrix} u = x & v = e^x \\ du = dx & dv = e^xdx\end{matrix}\end{align*}

and so it follows that

\begin{align*}\int x e^x dx = xe^x - \int e^x dx = xe^x - e^x + C= (x - 1)e^x + C\end{align*}

If we then put that into the definition of the average value, we find
that the average value is given by

\begin{align*}\frac{1}{2}\int_0^2 xe^x\, dx = \frac{1}{2}(x - 1)e^x|_0^2 = \frac{1}{2}\big((2 - 1)e^2 - (0 - 1)e^0\big) = \frac{1}{2}(e^2 + 1)\end{align*}

